                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-322-off1792 t18270913-322-crimeloc1795"></join>. On the 25th of August, between nine and ten o'clock in the evening, I saw the prisoner pulling these handkerchiefs off the line; several persons were in the shop; he put them under his jacket, and was walking out, when I caught hold of the end of them, and stopped him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-322-person2407">
                  THOMAS 
                  HALL
               <interp inst="t18270913-322-person2407" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-322-person2407" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-322-person2407" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was at home. I had driven the prisoner away from the shop twice within half an hour; he appeared much intoxicated, but when he was taken five men could not handcuff him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-322-person2408">
                  THOMAS 
                  SAPWELL
               <interp inst="t18270913-322-person2408" type="surname" value="SAPWELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-322-person2408" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-322-person2408" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I had been watching the prisoner - he tried to get some other handkerchiefs, but could not; he then went into the shop, and took these, I secured him with difficulty.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I went in to buy two yellow handkerchiefs - Mr. Hall would not let me have them.</p>
